{"summary":"Accept all three amendments. The test synchronization concern and retry-progress aggregation issue are real robustness/correctness defects; the clone-removal note is a valid low-risk cleanup.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-7-8c8af466","decision":"accept","rationale":"The test does not actually prove lock contention. After spawning thread 2, `recv_timeout(Duration::from_millis(100))` only shows that the thread did not finish within 100 ms; under scheduler delay or heavy CI load, that can pass even if thread 2 never reached the lock attempt. An explicit barrier or pre-lock signal would make the serialization claim deterministic and prevent a vacuous pass."},{"amendment_id":"fr-7-0047ba65","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is technically correct. In `persist_plan`, the closure passed to `with_milestone_write_lock` is `FnOnce`, so the owned `plan_hash: String` can be moved into the closure and then into `snapshot.plan_hash` without cloning. The same applies to `outcome_detail` in `update_task_run`. It is not a correctness bug, but it is a real unnecessary allocation on a hot path and a straightforward maintainability cleanup."},{"amendment_id":"fr-7-368e3c97","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a substantive correctness issue. `reconcile_snapshot_from_lineage` derives milestone progress by counting every normalized lineage row, but `collapse_task_run_attempts` only merges legacy start/terminal pairs for a single attempt. Distinct retries remain as separate terminal rows, so a bead that failed and later succeeded can contribute to both `failed_beads` and `completed_beads`. That contradicts the documented meaning of `MilestoneProgress` as bead-level state and makes `status.json` reflect attempt history rather than current milestone progress."}]}